  "prompt": "What is the difference between active voice and passive voice?",
  "response": "The difference between active voice and passive voice lies primarily in the structure of the sentence and the focus on the subject and object.\n\n1. **Active Voice**:\n   - In active voice, the subject of the sentence performs the action. The structure typically follows a clear Subject-Verb-Object format.\n   - Example: \"The cat (subject) chased (verb) the mouse (object).\"\n   - Here, the cat is doing the action of chasing.\n\n2. **Passive Voice**:\n   - In passive voice, the subject of the sentence is acted upon by the verb. The focus shifts from the doer to the receiver of the action. The structure often follows Subject-Verb-By-Agent format (though the agent can be omitted).\n   - Example: \"The mouse (subject) was chased (verb) by the cat (agent).\"\n   - In this case, the mouse is the focus of the sentence, and the action is being done to it.\n\nIn summary, active voice emphasizes who is doing the action, while passive voice emphasizes who is receiving the action.",
